<head><title>For The Record  -- NR</title></head>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H2>For The Record</H2></CENTER>
<HR>
28-August-1995


<P>


<P>
<LI>As House recessed for August, <B> Bill Clinton </B>blamed <B> Newt Gingrich </B>for ``delay, debate, and division.'' . . . Angry remarks of Minority Whip <B> David Bonior</B>(D., Mich.) convinced GOP lawmakers they were doing something right: ``The most hard-hearted, short-sighted, suck-up-to-the-rich-and-soak-the-middle-class Congress in American history.'' Bonior's wrath is explained in part by fifth Democratic defection to GOP ranks -- Rep. <B> Billy Tauzin</B>(La.). Now considered front-runner for seat of retiring Sen. <B> Bennett Johnston</B>(D.), Tauzin blamed Bonior and other Democratic leaders for driving conservatives out of party. <B> Mike Parker</B>(D., Miss.) will be next defector. . . . Anger of Dems, like Bonior and Minority Leader <B> Richard Gephardt</B>(Mo.), at Clinton for putting forward own balanced-budget plan (instead of just bashing away at GOP's) was badly misplaced, according to<B> Richard Morris</B>, Clinton's new political guru.<I> U.S. News & World Report</I> says Morris is telling Prez the plan resulted in a ``permanent'' 10-point increase in approval rating -- also, that Clinton's new anti-crime ads have resulted in ``7-point boost in each state where they have run.'' . . . Former political advisors now replaced by Morris and others are not leaving town broke. A <I> Boston Globe </I>report -- gleefully faxed far and wide by GOP Chairman <B> Haley Barbour </B>-- reports 30-month billings by Clinton political geniuses of yesteryear: consultants <B> James Carville </B>and<B> Paul Begala</B>, $450,000; pollster<B> Stanley Greenberg</B>, $4.5 million; and media maven<B> Mandy Grunwald</B>, $5 million. . . . Liberals face future funding problems, though. <I> Newsweek </I>cites Mellman Group and A.B. Data Group report that says average age of donors to liberal groups is 65, with 40 per cent dead in 10 years.
<P>
<LI>Network notes: ABC anchorman <B> Peter Jennings </B>got pasted for one-sided Hiroshima special criticizing U.S. use of A-bomb. Even <I> Washington Post </I>reviewer <B> Ken Ringle </B>described show as ``an ingenue's stroll down the narrow tunnels of academic revisionism with only occasional intimations that larger truths may lie outside.'' . . . CBS anchorman <B> Dan Rather </B>sees partisanship in Clinton's ethical/legal troubles. A lion of Watergate who never saw Seventies congressional investigations as Democratic plot to get<B> Richard Nixon</B>, Rather refers to current congressional probes as ``all-out Republican offensive on Whitewater.'' . . . National Public Radio correspondent <B> Nina Totenberg </B>-- who once screamed obscenities at Sen. <B> Alan Simpson</B>(R., Wyo.) for saying her stories were smearing judicial nominee <B> Clarence Thomas </B>-- is turning on the charm again. Noting recent objections by Sen. <B> Jesse Helms</B>(R., N.C.) to high funding levels for AIDS research,  Totenberg said: ``I think he ought to be worried about what's going on in the Good Lord's mind. Because if there is retributive justice, he'll get AIDS from a transfusion, or one of his grandchildren will get it.'' . . . Long critical of Fox TV's heavy emphasis on sexual themes, cultural conservatives are hoping <B> Rupert Murdoch </B>calls his office soon. Murdoch-owned Fox TV now running <B> Michael Moore's </B><I> TV Nation</I> -- which is also being praised by Murdoch-owned<I> N.Y. Post</I>. The baseball-cap-wearing Moore is former <I> Mother Jones </I>journalist who poses as average-guy observer to hide his hard-core leftism -- he's currently blasting GOP candidates for ``spirit of Nixon'' -- and anti - Middle America bigotry. (Moore's nasty film about hometown of Flint, Mich., <I> Roger and Me</I>, is all-time favorite of Hollywood liberals.)
<P>
<LI>Black America's Political Action Committee (BAMPAC) will host its first annual conference Sept. 24 - 25 at Hyatt Regency in Washington, D.C. Among speakers are founders <B> Alan Keyes </B>and<B> Phyllis Berry Myers</B>. Call 202-544-5355.
<P>
<LI><I> International Herald Tribune</I> will not fight $678,000 libel penalty by Singapore court. Former Prime Minister <B> Lee Kuan Yew </B>said paper's opinion piece about his regime was example of U.S. cultural imperialism and meant to ``dishonor'' him. . . . House hearings on restoration of Taiwan membership in UN being pushed by Rep. <B> Gerald Solomon</B>(R., N.Y.). . . . Asking State Dept. to deny <B> Fidel Castro </B>visa for UN visit, 25 members of Congress, led by Rep. <B> Richard Torricelli</B>(D., N.J.), called him ``a totalitarian Communist who has murdered, imprisoned, and tortured . . . for 36 years.'' . . .<B> Santiago Medina</B>, former campaign treasurer for Colombia President<B> Ernesto Samper</B>, says prez ordered him to take $6 million from drug cartel. Prior to election last year, U.S. State Dept. stopped Drug Enforcement Agency from releasing information showing Samper was tied to drug cartels. . . . International economists interviewed by Reuters are backing up recent claims by Saudi Arabia's King <B> Fahd </B>that his country will balance budget for first time since Gulf War. . . .  Famed anthropologist<B> Richard Leakey</B> -- who discovered oldest human skull -- has founded political party in Kenya. . . . <B> Alan Moreau </B>of the Paris Tourism Dept. says his office's ``Bonjour'' program -- a summertime be-nice-to-tourists campaign -- is working. ``Expectations are now worse than the reality,'' he says about Parisian reputation for rudeness.
<P>
<LI>Reflecting incredulity that it took her bosses four days to look in <B> Vincent Foster's </B>briefcase for suicide note, White House secretary <B> Linda R. Tripp </B>responded to another secretary's reference to ``slapstick comedy'' in the West Wing with this e-mail message: ``So it took until Monday to figure out it should be looked at? . . . And we're the support staff?'' -- OCD

