<head>
<title>Regional Conference Galvanizes Activists</title>
</head>

<body>

<h2>Regional Confrence Galvanizes Activists</h2>
<h4>Over 400 Eager Students Hear North, Evans, Robinson</h4>

<img alt="Students.gif" src="students.gif">
<hr><i>Egar Texas students turn out in force for Young America's Foundation regional confrence in Dallas.  Over 400 students came to hear from <b>Ollie North, Michael Williams, Stan Evans, Ron Robinson, Senator Steve Symms, Floyd Brown</b> and others during the two-day event.</i>
<hr>

Taking its campus road trip to the heart of Texas, <b>Young America's Foundation</b> headed to Dallas for a conference with over 400 college students in attendance on February 17 and 18.<p>

<b>Colonel Oliver North</b> kicked off the event Friday night with a rousing speech to students about the future of the conservative movement. He said that while conservatives had a great victory in Novernber, they need to stay true to their principles and keep their word to the American people. He called the Contract with America "something unique in American political experience." This is the first time government has established a "set of parameters" on which to govern and by which individuslc will be judged. Colonel North encouraged his primarily student audience to get involved in public policy
and make a difference.<p>

<img alt="Ollie North" src="north.gif"><br>
<hr>
<i><b>Ollie North</b> joins students during the cofrence, urging them to be active on their campuses and to make a difference.</i><hr>

Saturday began with a lecture by former <b>Senator Steve Symms</b>, president of Freedom Alliance, on the ability of young people to have a voice in policy making. He cited his career in politics which began at
age 34, when as a virtual unknown in the political world, he ran for and won a seat in the United States
House of Representatives.<p>

<b>Michael Williams</b>, assistant secretary for civil rights for the Department of Education during the Bush Administration, followed with a lively discussion on political correctness and racial issues on campuses. He encouraged students to seek support in the black student community. He said, "You will put out your hand and they will slap it; that will happen again and again. But if you persist, you will reach them."<p>

<img alt="Michael Williams" src="mwill.gif"><hr>
<i><b>Michael Williams</b> talks with a student following his remarks on political correctness and racial issues on campus.</i><hr>

Foundation President <b>Ron Robinson</b> and Director of Program Development <b>Kate Obenshain Griffin</b> talked to students about the urgency and opportunities of campus activism, saying now that conservatives have taken over Congress, liberals are turning their attention to the campuses and the next generation with renewed vigor. In order to challenge their leftist professors, Mr. Robinson urged students to take the initiative in educating themselves about conservative ideals by reading conservative journals and books. He told student activists to surround themselves with supportive people who would work with them in promoting conservatism on campus. And he encouraged students to "be enthusiastic about your ideas and convictions. Only then will you capture the interest and imagination of your fellow students whom you are trying to reach."<p>

Mr. Robinson warned students to remember as they seek to reach other students that a perfect audience is never assembled and that they need to reach out to a broad audience. And finally, citing the examples of <b>William Buckley</b> and <b>Rush Limbaugh</b>, Mr. Robinson told students, "Start your own organization if your conservative voice is not being heard through existing ones." Instead of working for the <i>New Yorker</i> magazine and the <i>Atlantic Monthly</i>, Mr. Buckley started up his own publication, <i>National Review</i>. Similarly, instead of working his way up with ABC and CBS news Limbaugh started his own radio show.<p>

Following an introduction by Foundation board member and Texas native <b>Wayne Thorburn</b>, <b>M. Stanton Evans</b> delivered the luncheon address, discussing his book, <b>The Theme Is Freedom</b>. He chroIlicled and corrected the fallacies of the liberal history lesson students are taught regarding the development of our nation and the roots of the freedom we enjoy.<p>

<b>Floyd Brown</b>, president of Citizens United, spoke on the Clinton presidency, detailing the Whitewater controversy and providing insights on the Mexican bailout. He chided Mr. Clinton for misleading the American people and disgracing the office of the president.<p>

<b>Tom Pauken</b>, chairman of the Texas Republican Party, closed the conference discussine the continuation of the Reagan Revolution. He also talked about his book <b>The Thirty Years War</b>.<p>

<img alt="Michelle Sharp" src="sharp.gif"><hr>
<i><b>Michelle Sharp,</b> Young America's Foundation's program officer for lectures, speaks to students about bringing prominent conservative speakers to their campuses.</i><hr>

University of Dallas student and Young America's Foundation activist <b>Tom Lagarde</b> said, "We need more events like this one. Conservative students from across the region have the chance to get together with one another and find out how students are coping with different situations. And we get to hear from more great conservative speakers in one day than most would hear from in four years at school."<p>

Each year, Young America's Foundation hosts regional student conferences in several states around the country.<p><p>
