<body>

<h2>On the Home Front</h2>

<img src="cartoon.gif"><hr>
<i>In February, Young America's Foundation President <b>Ron Robinson</b> called on Rutgers University President <b>Francis Lawrence</b> to resign.  After enacting a speech code which threatened students with expulsion or suspension if they made a statement likely "to cause annoymance ... even if communicative in nature," Mr. Lawrence violated it.  Students were outraged when he stated that minorities don't "have the genetic, hereditary background to have a higher [SAT] average."  While Young America's Foundation is unalterably opposed to speech codes designed to restrict the free flow of ideas, Mr. Robinson said that college administrators who impose these regulations should abide by them.</i><hr>

<h4>Novak To Be Flowers Lecturer</h4>

Young America's Foundation is pleased to announce that <b>Robert Novak</b> will be the featured speaker for the <b>1995 William H. Flowers, Jr. Lecture Series</b>. Mr. Novak is one of the country's most respected journalists and political commentators. Through the series, he will be speaking at eight schools.<p>

<h4>Hermann Lecture Serced Features Mees</h4>

<b>The Honorable Edwin Meese III</b> is this year's <b>Grover Hermann Freedom
Lecturer</b>. Mr. Meese served under President Reagan as the 75th Attorney General of the United States. He has spoken already at Wittenburg College, the University of Oklahoma and Florida State University through the series.<p>

<h4>Short, Griffen, Rosenberger Return To Foundation</h4>

<b>Marc Short</b> returned to Young America's Foundation as national director after serving as <b>Oliver North's</b> director of the Virginia Finance Committee during Northis senatorial campaign. Marc originally joined the Foundation as national director after graduating from Washington and Lee University in 1992.<p>

<b>Kate Obenshain Griffin</b> concluded her tenure as Governor George Allen's special assistant for policy development and returned to the Foundation as director of program development. In 1991, after graduating from the University of Virginia, Kate became the Foundation's lecture director.<p>

In the midst of his high-profile Supreme Court case against the University of Virginia, <b>Ron Rosenberger</b>joins the Foundation as a program officer. Ron served as an intern at the Foundation while a student at the University of Virginia. As a campus activist at Wa, Ron founded <i>Wide Awake</i>, a publication which was denied student activities funds on the basis of it being a "religious activity." Ron filed suit agains UVa and his case is currently before the Supreme Court.<p>

<h4>Liddy, O'Rourke, Quayle, Snow Join Speaker Program</h4>

<b>G. Gordon Liddy, P.J. O'Rourke, Marilyn Quayle and Tony Snow</b> have joined Young America's Foundation's Speakers Program. The program is the largest conservative speakers program in the nation, offering alternative viewpoints to college students. If you are interested in learning more about the Foundation's speakers program, please contact <b>Michelle Sharp</b>: 1-800-292-9231.<p>

<h4>Foundation Activist Elected Student Body President</h4>

Young America's Foundation activist and former intern <b>Bill Gullan</b> has been elected president of the student body at Davidson College in North Carolina. While an intern at the Foundation, Bill was conference director for the 1 994 Annual Student Summer Conference in D.C. <p><p>

