<title>Daily Commentary - December 24, 1996</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
December 24, 1996</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

Today is Christmas Eve, and across the country airports and
highways are jammed.  People are heading home for the holidays,
hoping to make it in time for Christmas.  But today there are
tens of thousands of Americans who can only dream of those airports
and highways -- of those homecomings that matter so much.

<p>

Those are the men and women of our Armed Forces.  America
may be at peace, but still there are an incredible 237,000 American
soldiers scattered across the globe.  We're all aware of the contingent
in Bosnia, but the majority of our sons and daughters overseas
are elsewhere.  They are serving with NATO, manning submarines
under polar ice, sweating as military attaches in Africa, or guarding
the truce line in Korea.

<p>

We are not at war, but none of these soldiers serve in safety.
As the publisher of the <I>American Legion Magazine</I> pointed
out recently, the great irony is that the very status of our forces
as emissaries of peace makes them targets of war.  To these men
and women, we say, &quot;Merry Christmas, and may God bless you
and your families.&quot;

<p>

For the Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with today's
Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call 1-800-225-4008.
That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

