<html>

<title>Daily Commentary - December 26, 1996</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
December 26, 1996</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

The newspapers have been filled lately with all sorts of
stories about questionable political contributions from Asian
sources to President Clinton's reelection and legal defense funds.
The stories raise major issues that go to the integrity of our
political system, and they should be thoroughly investigated.
Unfortunately, there's a danger in all of this that Asian-Americans
as a whole will be falsely stigmatized.

<p>

That makes the story of Kingston Technology even more important.
John Tu and David Sun are business partners who lost $2,000,000
in the 1987 stock market plunge.  Tu is a Chinese immigrant. 
Rather than despair, he and Sun restarted their California-based
business with just $4,000.  Through hard work and ingenuity, they
rebuilt their company and turned it into an American success story.
They just sold the company for $1.5 billion.  And get this, they
are giving their employees an average bonus of $75,000.

<p>

That's some Christmas present -- and it's an even more poignant
reminder that it's not race, but ethics that count.

<p>

For the Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with
today's Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call
1-800-225-4008.  That number again: 1-800-225-4008.

<p>

