<html>

<title>Daily Commentary - December 30, 1996</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
December 30, 1996</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

I get caught up in holiday shopping as much as anyone, and
I have the bills to prove it.  So naturally my talk today is about
how we make too much of material goods during this spiritual season.
But I have special reason to emphasize that theme.

<p>

Just before Christmas, we received one of those calls in
the night every parent dreads.  The phone rang with the news that
our daughters, Elyse and Sarah, had been in an accident on the
interstate 75 miles from our home.  They were returning from Elyse's
college, and it was a night of sleet and slick roads.  The car
had spun across the highway and been rear-ended. The car was
totaled, but fortunately, both girls' injuries were minor -- a
bad head bump and some whiplash.  But it came home quickly to
us how easily our girls could have been killed on that highway
home.

<p>

The heart of Christmas is the miracle of the child Jesus,
God becoming man.  That miracle was even more meaningful this
year at the Bauer house, all because of what did -- and didn't
-- happen on a dark and icy road.

<p>

For the Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with
today's Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call
1-800-225-4008.  That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

