<P><center>
<H2>Illegal and Illegals</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>
<blockquote>



"Barbara Coe, a leading proponent of immigration reform in California, was threatened with legal action by the Justice Department, the Orange County Registrar's Office, and immigrant advocacy groups for 'intimidating voters' on Election Day.
<P> 
	"Her crime? Distributing fliers that proclaimed: 'Only citizens can vote! Violators will be prosecuted!'
<P>
	"Latino groups saw her campaign as a blatant, racist effort to intimidate legitimate voters, many of whom were new citizens casting their first votes. But Mrs. Coe, 62, a Huntington Beach grandmother, said she felt the fliers were necessary to combat voter fraud after hearing from Hispanic members of the California Coalition for Immigration Reform, which she founded and chairs. . . .
<P>
	"In her view, the problem is twofold. Many immigrants are unaware that noncitizens cannot vote. Others, however, 'know it's against the law, but they don't care. They know there's no prosecution. There are no safeguards,' she said. 
<P>
	"She already has obtained a list of 18 illegal immigrants who voted, compiled by a social worker on duty at a local polling place, she said. . . .
<P>
	"An official from the Justice Department's civil-rights division called and interviewed her for more than an hour about complaints they'd received about her fliers. . . .
<P>
	"Then the Orange County registrar of voters called. 'She was just ballistic,' Mrs. Coe recalled. 'She said, If I get one complaint of voter intimidation, I'm going to prosecute you to the full extent of the law.'
<p>
	"Likewise, California Secretary of State Bill Jones put her on notice that he would not tolerate any intimidation activities. 'Interfering with any individual's right to vote . . . is a crime,' he wrote." . . .
<P>
Ruth Larson, <I>The Washington Times</I>, December 1, 1996 
	
</blockquote>
