<TITLE>Outrage du Jour</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<CENTER>
<img src="/nationalreview/images/outrage.gif" ALT="Outrage du Jour">
<br>
<br>
<HR width=50%> 
<!-----------------Townhall------------------------------>
<I>December 5, 1996</I></center>
<BR>
<BR>

<P><center>
<H2>Ivory Towering Inferno</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>
<blockquote>
	"The Young America's Foundation of Herndon, Va., has published 'Comedy and tragedy,' a list of some of the courses available at the nation's institutions of higher learning. . . .
<P>
	"Not surprisingly, some of the course descriptions that standout, even in this amazing list, come from the University of Massachusetts at Amherst, locally called Zoo Mass, where the education department offers three different courses on 'Special Issues in Education,' including two fairly recent concerns of the left, 'HandicapismDynamics of Handicapism on Personal and Institutional Levels,' 'HeterosexismDynamics of Heterosexism on Personal and Institutional Levels,' and third, that timeworn leftist obsession, 'ClassismDynamics of Classism on Personal and Institutional Levels.'
<P>
	"But from the University of California at Santa Cruz comes the scariest offering. A Big Brotheror should we say, Big Sister-minded education department presents students with Education 189: 'Monitoring Girls for Science and Math Equity: This six-credit, multiple-term course provides opportunities for women students from any discipline to mentor girls in local K12 classrooms. Mentors are trained to promote equity in science, math, and technology.' Gifted boys had better learn to keep quiet or face fierce reprimand."
<P>
Stephen Goode, <I>Insight</I>, October 28, 1996

</blockquote>
<!------------------------------------------------------------>
<P>
